Talk to a financial advisor for more information.

entity.name: Open a SEP IRA
entity.description:
A SEP (Simplified Employee Pension) IRA would be your best choice. It generally has no initial setup fee nor annual maintenance fee. The employer can contribute up to 25% of compensation up to a maximum of $55,000 annually (2018 limits). 

NOTE: Contributions are a percentage of compensation and MUST be an equal percentage across employees. For example, there is no way to contribute $10,000 to all employees' accounts if they have different compensation amounts.  You can set the contribution amount at 10% and all employees' accounts would receive 10% of their compensation. If this is not ideal for your situation, then we recommend going with a plan that allows employee contributions.

entity.name: Open a SIMPLE IRA
entity.description:
While the setup fees and annual maintenance fees tend to be lower than a company sponsored 401(k), a SIMPLE (Savings Incentive Match Plan for Employees) IRA has lower annual contribution limits. 

Employees can contribute up to $12,500 annually vs $18,500 in a 401(k).

Employers may make matching contributions up to 3% of compensation or a non-elective contribution (doesn't require employee contribution) of 2% up to $5,500.

Note: Limits shown are are 2018 IRS limits.

entity.name: Open a company sponsored 401(k)
entity.description:
While the setup fees and annual maintenance fees tend to be higher than a SIMPLE IRA, a company sponsored 401(k) has higher annual contribution limits. 

Employees can contribute up to $18,500 annually vs $12,500 in a SIMPLE IRA.

Employers may make matching or profit sharing contributions up to 25% of compensation up to a total employee/employer contribution of $55,000.

Note: Limits shown are are 2018 IRS limits.
